A short gown;
a herald's
coat; a surcoat.

A piece cut out of the whole;
a share of one's substance paid by way of
tribute; a toll or tax. Cowell.

In old English law. A
seller of wine; one who kept a house or shop
for the sale of wine,

Sax. In old English law.
Land of a thane or Saxon noble; land granted by the crown to a thane or lord. Cowell;
1 Reeve, Eng. Law, 5.,

Lat. In
the civil law. A third person intervening;
a third person who comes in between the parties to a sult; one who interpleads. Gilbert's Forum Rom. 47.

A person is said to be testable when he has capacity to make a will;
a man of twenty-one years of age and of
sane mind is testable.

A place tilled or cultivated;
land under cultivation, as opposed to lands
lying fallow or in pasture.

v. Lat. To go, or pass over;
to pass from one thing, person, or place. to
another.

Lat. Baseness; infamy;
immorality; turpitude.

Tuta est custodia qus sibimet ocreditur. Hob. 340. That guardianship is secure which is intrusted to itself alone.

